## Vibe coding needs a proper brief

The phrase "vibe coding" makes the process sound wonderfully casual. You describe what you want, an AI writes some code, and a website appears before the tea has gone cold. There is some truth in the speed, but not in the idea that the difficult thinking has disappeared.

In plain language, vibe coding means building software through a conversation with an AI coding tool. You explain an outcome, review what it produces, ask for changes and keep refining. It can turn an idea into a working interface much faster than starting every component from an empty file. That is useful. It is also very easy to build the wrong thing quickly.

A custom website still needs a clear purpose. Who needs to use it? What are they trying to find or do? Which content matters most? What has to be editable? What happens on a phone with a poor connection? What should happen if a form fails? These are not coding questions alone. They are product, content, design and business questions.

I think the combined workflow is where things become interesting. Strategy and requirements come first. Design gives those requirements a visible structure. AI-assisted coding then helps turn approved ideas into a functioning system. Testing and refinement reveal where our assumptions were wrong. Each part informs the next, but none of them should be skipped.

## Design tools still have a job

Figma, Adobe tools, sketches and wireframes remain useful because they let us explore without pretending that every idea is ready to become production code. Sometimes I need to compare several page structures quickly. Sometimes I need to establish typography, image treatment and spacing before worrying about application state. Sometimes a rough drawing is enough to expose a bad idea.

The design stage is not there to make a static picture that developers must copy blindly. It is there to make decisions visible. A good design system explains relationships: what is primary, what repeats, how content behaves at different widths and which parts should feel consistent across the site.

Once those decisions are strong enough, working in code can become another design medium. The browser gives immediate evidence. Type wraps differently at 390 pixels. A comfortable desktop interaction feels clumsy under a thumb. A beautiful animation uses too much processing power. That feedback is not a failure of the design. It is the design becoming real.

AI coding tools can shorten the distance between the visual idea and that evidence. I can test a responsive composition, inspect the result, adjust the system and keep the useful parts. The value is not that the first answer is perfect. It rarely is. The value is that more of the time can go into comparing, testing and improving.

## Custom code is not automatically the right answer

WordPress remains useful. Many organisations know it, many teams can support it and its plugin ecosystem solves common publishing needs. If a client needs a familiar traditional editor, established integrations and access to a large pool of developers, WordPress may be the sensible choice.

Shopify remains a strong choice for many ecommerce businesses because it brings together products, payments, stock, orders and a mature operational system. Rebuilding all of that from scratch to prove that custom code is fashionable would be an expensive way to learn what platforms are for.

There are also no-code and low-code tools that suit straightforward marketing sites, quick campaigns and teams that want visual control. The point is not to declare one winner.

The question is what the website needs to do, who needs to maintain it and what trade-offs are acceptable. A custom-coded system can make sense when the experience is unusual, performance matters, the interface has specific behaviour or a standard theme would force the content into the wrong shape. It can also avoid a stack of plugins that each solve five percent of the problem while introducing another five percent of uncertainty.

My informed view is that more businesses will consider custom systems as AI-assisted development reduces some of the cost and friction. That does not mean every business should choose one. Lowering the effort required to produce code does not remove hosting, accessibility, security, maintenance or content responsibilities.

## The platform matters less than the judgement around it

People often begin a website conversation by asking whether it should be WordPress, Shopify, Webflow or something custom. It is a reasonable question, but it arrives too early.

A technically impressive stack cannot rescue unclear navigation, weak typography or content that answers the wrong questions. A polished design cannot rescue a checkout that breaks. Fast AI output cannot rescue a team that has not agreed what success means.

The more useful question is whether the person or team making the site understands enough of the whole system. They need to see the relationship between visual hierarchy and usable code. They need to know when an image is damaging performance, when an animation is interfering with reading and when a request that sounds simple will create a maintenance problem later.

Production knowledge matters here. Design decisions eventually meet files, browsers, devices, content editors and real people. A concept that only works in one perfect screenshot is not a complete website design.

This is also why AI does not remove the need for developers. Strong developers understand architecture, data, security, testing and the consequences of technical choices. AI can assist with implementation, but someone still needs to recognise unsafe code, fragile shortcuts and systems that will become painful to maintain.

The best projects respect each kind of expertise. The workflow may become more fluid, and one multidisciplinary person may cover more ground than before, but the need for judgement increases when output becomes cheap.

## Working faster should create more room for refinement

Speed is useful when we spend the saved time well. If AI helps produce a component in twenty minutes instead of two hours, the result should not simply be twenty minutes of work shipped sooner. It can mean more time checking keyboard access, testing a smaller phone, refining the copy, compressing imagery or asking whether the component should exist at all.

I use AI-assisted coding as a practical collaborator. It can help explore an approach, explain unfamiliar code, find a repetitive error or build a first version. I still need to read the result, understand what it changes and test the behaviour. When it suggests a fashionable animation that adds no value, the correct prompt may be "remove it".

There is also a discipline to keeping the system coherent. Without it, a conversational coding workflow can create five slightly different buttons, random spacing values and duplicated logic. The site may work, but it becomes harder to change safely. A shared design language and clear component architecture matter even more when new code can appear so quickly.

## A practical way to choose your website approach

For a business planning a new website, I would start with needs rather than platforms.

Write down the important user journeys. Decide who owns the content. Identify the integrations and legal requirements. Be honest about the budget for maintenance, not only launch. Then explore the visual and technical approach that fits those conditions.

If WordPress gives the team the familiarity and editing workflow it needs, use it well. If Shopify removes unnecessary risk from ecommerce operations, let it do that job. If a custom interface can communicate the business more clearly and avoid fighting a theme, consider custom code.

Vibe coding changes what can be built and who can participate in building it. I find that exciting. It brings design and implementation closer together and makes experimentation more accessible. But it works best when it sits inside a serious process: thinking, designing, coding, testing and refining.

The tools can make the hands faster. They do not decide where the hands should go.
